  <!-- Section 1 -->
  <div class="fio-card">
    <h2 class="fio-h2">1) What Does “Rolling a Covered Call” Mean?</h2>
    <p class="fio-p">
      <strong>Rolling</strong> means you close your current covered call and open a new covered call (same stock) with a new strike,
      a new expiration, or both — usually as a single “roll” order.
    </p>

    <div class="fio-grid2">
      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h3 class="fio-h3">Why people roll</h3>
        <ul class="fio-list">
          <li>Collect additional premium (more income)</li>
          <li>Extend time (buy more time for the trade)</li>
          <li>Adjust strike to manage assignment risk</li>
          <li>Keep a structured plan instead of guessing</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h3 class="fio-h3">Types of rolls (plain English)</h3>
        <ul class="fio-list">
          <li><strong>Roll out:</strong> same strike, later expiration</li>
          <li><strong>Roll up and out:</strong> higher strike + later expiration</li>
          <li><strong>Roll down and out:</strong> lower strike + later expiration</li>
          <li><strong>Adjust expiration:</strong> move closer/farther based on premium and risk</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 2 -->
  <div class="fio-card">
    <h2 class="fio-h2">2) When Should You Roll?</h2>
    <p class="fio-p">
      Here are the most common “roll situations.” Use these as decision rules — not emotions.
    </p>

    <div class="fio-grid2">
      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h3 class="fio-h3">A) Call is ITM and assignment risk is rising</h3>
        <ul class="fio-list">
          <li>Stock moved above your strike</li>
          <li>You still want to keep the shares</li>
          <li>You want to shift to a higher strike and/or more time</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="fio-p fio-note fio-muted">
          Reality check: assignment isn’t “bad” if you’re okay selling at your strike. Rolling is optional.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h3 class="fio-h3">B) Expiration is approaching</h3>
        <ul class="fio-list">
          <li>You want to avoid last-minute volatility surprises</li>
          <li>You want to extend the trade and collect more premium</li>
          <li>You prefer a cleaner weekly routine (instead of chaos on expiration day)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h3 class="fio-h3">C) Premium is mostly “captured”</h3>
        <ul class="fio-list">
          <li>If the call has lost most of its value, you can consider closing it and selling a new one</li>
          <li>This is how covered calls become repeatable income</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="fio-p fio-note fio-muted">
          Many traders use a profit target on the short call (example: buying it back after most of the premium is earned).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h3 class="fio-h3">D) Volatility changed</h3>
        <ul class="fio-list">
          <li>Higher volatility can increase premiums (good for selling calls)</li>
          <li>Lower volatility can reduce premium (you may choose fewer adjustments)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="fio-divider"></div>

    <div class="fio-mini">
      <h3 class="fio-h3">Roll vs. Close (Fast Rule)</h3>
      <div class="fio-tablewrap">
        <table class="fio-table" aria-label="Roll vs Close decision table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>If you want…</th>
              <th>Then consider…</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Keep shares + collect more premium</td>
              <td><strong>Rolling</strong> (often up and out)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>You’re okay selling at strike</td>
              <td>Let it assign or <strong>close</strong> and reset</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Stock looks weak / you don’t want more downside exposure</td>
              <td><strong>Close</strong> and reduce risk (don’t force a roll)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>You would have to pay a large net debit</td>
              <td>Pause — rolling for a big debit needs a clear reason</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 3 -->
  <div class="fio-card">
    <h2 class="fio-h2">3) How to Roll a Covered Call (Step-by-Step)</h2>

    <div class="fio-mini">
      <h3 class="fio-h3">Step 1: Close the Existing Call</h3>
      <ul class="fio-list">
        <li>You <strong>buy to close</strong> the current short call</li>
        <li>Use liquid strikes when possible (tighter bid/ask helps)</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="fio-p fio-note fio-muted">If spreads are wide, avoid rushing. Liquidity matters.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="fio-divider"></div>

    <div class="fio-mini">
      <h3 class="fio-h3">Step 2: Choose the New Strike + Expiration</h3>
      <ul class="fio-list">
        <li><strong>Roll out</strong> to collect more premium and buy time</li>
        <li><strong>Roll up and out</strong> if stock ran above your strike and you want more upside room</li>
        <li><strong>Roll down and out</strong> only with a clear plan (can increase assignment risk sooner)</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="fio-divider"></div>
      <p class="fio-p"><strong>Net credit vs. net debit:</strong></p>
      <ul class="fio-list">
        <li><strong>Net credit</strong> = you receive more premium on the new call than it costs to close the old call</li>
        <li><strong>Net debit</strong> = it costs more to close the old call than you receive from the new call</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="fio-p fio-note fio-muted">
        Many traders prefer rolling for a <strong>net credit</strong>. If you’re paying a debit, be clear why (more upside room, more time, avoiding assignment, etc.).
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="fio-divider"></div>

    <div class="fio-mini">
      <h3 class="fio-h3">Step 3: Place the Roll Order</h3>
      <ul class="fio-list">
        <li>Most brokers offer a “roll” ticket (it’s just close + open combined)</li>
        <li>Double-check: <strong>same symbol</strong>, correct strike(s), correct expiration(s)</li>
        <li>Confirm whether it’s a <strong>credit</strong> or <strong>debit</strong> before sending</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="fio-divider"></div>

    <!-- ✅ FIXED: Inline SVG checks (NOT emoji) -->
    <div class="fio-card fio-soft">
      <h3 class="fio-h3">Roll Order Checklist (Copy/Paste)</h3>
      <ul class="fio-list fio-note">
        <li><span class="fio-check"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 6L9 17l-5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></span>I own 100 shares per covered call</li>
        <li><span class="fio-check"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 6L9 17l-5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></span>I know my current strike + expiration</li>
        <li><span class="fio-check"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 6L9 17l-5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></span>I know the new strike + expiration I’m choosing</li>
        <li><span class="fio-check"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 6L9 17l-5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></span>I confirmed if the roll is a net credit or net debit</li>
        <li><span class="fio-check"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 6L9 17l-5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></span>I’m okay with assignment risk on the new strike</li>
        <li><span class="fio-check"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 6L9 17l-5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></span>I logged the new position details</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 4 -->
  <div class="fio-card">
    <h2 class="fio-h2">4) Key Rolling Strategies</h2>

    <div class="fio-grid2">
      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h3 class="fio-h3">1) Rolling Up and Out <span class="fio-chip">More Upside Room</span></h3>
        <ul class="fio-list">
          <li>Best when the stock is trending up and you want to stay in the trade</li>
          <li>You move to a higher strike and a later expiration</li>
          <li>Goal: collect more premium while giving shares room to run</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h3 class="fio-h3">2) Rolling Out <span class="fio-chip">More Time</span></h3>
        <ul class="fio-list">
          <li>Best when the stock is near your strike and you want more time</li>
          <li>Same strike, later expiration</li>
          <li>Goal: collect additional premium and reduce “expiration week pressure”</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h3 class="fio-h3">3) Rolling Down and Out <span class="fio-chip">Risk Adjustment</span></h3>
        <ul class="fio-list">
          <li>Used when the stock dropped and you want to adjust income profile</li>
          <li>Requires extra caution (can increase assignment risk if price rebounds)</li>
          <li>Goal: rebuild premium, but don’t force it on weak stocks</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="fio-mini">
        <h3 class="fio-h3">4) Rolling Early vs. Late</h3>
        <ul class="fio-list">
          <li><strong>Early roll:</strong> calmer decisions, less chaos</li>
          <li><strong>Late roll:</strong> more theta, but higher “event risk” near expiration</li>
          <li>Goal: stay structured — avoid panic rolls</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 5 -->
  <div class="fio-card">
    <h2 class="fio-h2">5) Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
    <ul class="fio-list">
      <li>Rolling too soon (without a clear reason)</li>
      <li>Rolling too late (panic rolling during expiration volatility)</li>
      <li>Paying a <strong>large net debit</strong> without a plan</li>
      <li>Rolling on weak stocks that could continue dropping</li>
      <li>Overcomplicating rolls when closing + resetting is cleaner</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 6 -->
  <div class="fio-card">
    <h2 class="fio-h2">6) Live Example Checklist (Execution)</h2>
    <p class="fio-p">Use this list during the video walkthrough:</p>
    <ol class="fio-list">
      <li>Identify current call (strike + expiration)</li>
      <li>Confirm stock price vs strike (ITM/OTM)</li>
      <li>Choose the “why” (more premium, more time, more upside room)</li>
      <li>Select new strike + expiration</li>
      <li>Confirm net credit / net debit before submitting</li>
      <li>Place roll order and log new position</li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <!-- Section 7 (✅ FIXED inline checks inside sentence) -->
  <div class="fio-card fio-soft">
    <h2 class="fio-h2">Final Takeaways</h2>
