      <span class="fio-check"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 6L9 17l-5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></span>
      Rolling is a tool — not a rule.<br>
      <span class="fio-check"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 6L9 17l-5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></span>
      Prefer a <strong>net credit</strong> when possible (unless you have a clear reason).<br>
      <span class="fio-check"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 6L9 17l-5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></span>
      Use <strong>roll up and out</strong> when you want more upside room on a strong stock.<br>
      <span class="fio-check"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 6L9 17l-5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></span>
      Use <strong>roll out</strong> when you want more time and more premium.<br>
      <span class="fio-check"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 6L9 17l-5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg></span>
      Always ask: <strong>“Should I roll… or should I close and reset?”</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

